# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 29, 1776.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Hanover County Patrick Henry defeated Thomas Nelson Jr. and John Page.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election took place forty-five days after the adoption of the Lee Resolution by the Fifth Virginia Convention declaring the independence of the United Colonies from Great Britain.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of Virginia had been adopted by the convention the same day and went into effect immediately.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution called for the governor of Virginia to be elected by the votes of the Virginia General Assembly meeting in joint session.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention, as the provisional legislature of the commonwealth, performed this function in the election of 1776.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1830, the governor served a term of one year, renewable no more than three times in a seven-year period.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Henry was reelected four times: twice consecutively in 1777 and 1778, and again in 1784 and 1785, to serve a total of five consecutive terms in office.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fifth Virginia Convention convened in Williamsburg on May 6, 1776, amidst increasingly widespread support for independence among the Patriots who supported the American Revolution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 15, 1776, the convention approved a resolution instructing Virginia's delegates in the Second Continental Congress to support a formal declaration of independence absolving the Thirteen Colonies from their allegiance to the British Empire.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Congress voted to adopt the Lee Resolution on July 2, precipitating passage of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] While Congress debated independence, the Virginia Convention took action to establish the foundations for an independent commonwealth.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A Declaration of Rights was introduced in the convention on May 27 and adopted on June 12; on June 29, the delegates voted unanimously to adopt the proposed Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the Constitution now in place, elections for governor and Attorney General proceeded immediately.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of 1776 called for the governor and other executive officers to be elected by a joint session of the General Assembly, with a majority of votes cast necessary to elect the governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected for a term of one year and limited to three terms in a seven-year period.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the first General Assembly yet unelected, the Virginia Convention carried out the election of the first governor and Attorney General.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by secret ballot; in all, 106 delegates to the Virginia Convention cast votes for governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention elected Henry by a majority of 60 electoral votes to 45 for his nearest competitor, Thomas Nelson.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] George Wythe, James Madison, Bartholomew Dandridge, and William Roscoe Wilson Curl were appointed to inspect the ballots and inform Henry of his election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1777.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] An **acclamation** is a form of election that does not use a ballot.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] It derives from the ancient Roman word *acclamatio*, a kind of ritual greeting and expression of approval towards imperial officials in certain social contexts.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] The most frequent type of acclamation is a voice vote, in which the voting group is asked who favors and who opposes the proposed candidate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] In the event of a lack of opposition, the candidate is considered elected.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] In parliamentary procedure, acclamation is a form of unanimous consent.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] This form of election is most commonly associated with papal elections (see Acclamation in papal elections), though this method was discontinued by Pope John Paul II's apostolic constitution *Universi Dominici gregis*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] It is also sometimes found in the context of parliamentary decisions, or United States presidential nominating conventions (where it is often used to nominate the running mate and incumbent Presidents).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] In Canada, a candidate for a parliamentary, legislative or municipal position is said to be elected by acclamation if they have no opponents for the seat, an eventuality that rarely occurs federally, but is more common in legislative elections in the northern territories and municipal elections.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] The last instance of an acclamation in an election to the House of Commons of Canada was in 1957, when George Doucett was acclaimed in a by-election following the death of his predecessor William Gourlay Blair.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] Just two months before, Chesley William Carter had been the last person to be acclaimed in a general election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] In the Northwest Territories riding of Inuvik Boot Lake, Floyd Roland was returned by acclamation in two consecutive elections, in 2003 and 2007.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] Acclamations were ritual verbal expressions of approval and benediction in public (like gladiatorial games) and private life.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] The departure and return of imperial magistrates was, for example, accompanied by acclamation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] In the later Roman Empire, expressions of goodwill were reserved for the emperor and certain relatives, who were greeted in this manner during public appearances on special occasions such as their birthdays.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/acclamation] By the 4th century AD, acclamations were compulsory for high-level imperial officials.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Voters do not register by party in Virginia, and Virginia conducts open primaries where any voter may cast a ballot for either party.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Traditionally, political parties could choose which nomination method to use for each election, with the option to either participate in the state-run primary or conduct a party-run convention.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] A law which passed in 2021 and took effect in 2024 requires a party's method of nomination to make certain accommodations for absentee voters, and had the practical effect of outlawing party-run conventions.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In general elections, the party affiliations of local candidates do not appear on the ballot.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Candidates for federal, statewide, and General Assembly offices appear on the ballot with party designations.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Besides the Democratic Party of Virginia and the Republican Party of Virginia, other parties include the Libertarian Party of Virginia, Constitution Party of Virginia, Green Party of Virginia, and the Independent Greens of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Third parties and independents have benefited from electoral reform in Virginia, especially streamlined ballot access, and have made their presence known by appearing on statewide ballots and even winning seats to soil and water conservation district boards.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2009, Governor Tim Kaine proposed to authorize no-excuse early voting in Virginia elections, noting that 26 other states allow it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] On January 26, 2009, the bill passed the Democratic-controlled Senate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, the Republican-controlled House of delegates killed the proposal.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Governor Kaine worked with a coalition of civic groups to work to restore the voting rights of felons who were convicted of non-violent crimes in the past.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Kaine's staff reviewed each individual application from felons who had been out of prison for at least five years without an additional conviction.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] An estimated 366,000 Virginia citizens are disenfranchised due to a prior felony conviction.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Commonwealth of Virginia holds its state general elections on the first Tuesday after the first Monday in November (better known as Election Day) in every odd-numbered year.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] As a result of this, gubernatorial elections in Virginia systematically follow the quadrennial United States presidential election by one year.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] During general elections in Virginia, elections are held for the statewide executive positions of governor, lieutenant governor, and attorney general.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Elections are also held for legislative positions in the Senate of Virginia and the Virginia House of Delegates and the county-level offices of Commonwealth's attorney, sheriff, clerk of court, Treasurer, and Commissioner of the Revenue.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Officials elected to the House of Delegates serve a term of two years, and clerks of court are elected to eight-year terms.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] All other officials are elected for a term of four years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia's governor, lieutenant governor, and attorney general are elected at large every four years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] State senators and members of the House of Delegates are elected in single-member districts.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] County-level officials are elected by county.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia has 100 seats in its House of Delegates, and 40 seats in its Senate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After the American Civil War (1861–1865), Virginia was in political turmoil.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] 48 former counties now in West Virginia were gone, soon to be joined by two more.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Commonwealth of Virginia unsuccessfully appealed to the U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the remaining area, many citizens, mostly males of African American heritage, were newly enfranchised to vote.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Many others, primarily former Confederates, were initially disenfranchised.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Elections resumed after 5 years as a U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Military District, and control was chaotic.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the late 1870s, a coalition of Conservative Democrats, Republicans, and African Americans was assembled and the Readjuster Party took power for about 10 years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Senator William Mahone and the Readjuster Party lost control of Virginia politics around 1883, white Democrats regained the state legislature.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] They proceeded to use statute and a new constitution in 1901, with provisions such as a poll tax, residency requirements, and literacy test to disfranchise most African Americans and many poor whites.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Their disfranchisement lasted until after the passage of civil rights legislation in the mid-1960s.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] White Democrats created a one-party state, with a nearly unchallenged majority of state and most federal offices through the middle of the 20th century.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Byrd Organization headed by Harry F.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Byrd Sr. largely controlled statewide politics.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Through their leadership and activism in the Civil Rights Movement, African Americans gained national support for passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which provided Federal oversight and enforcement to maintain all citizens' ability to vote.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Under Section 5 of the Voting Rights Act, decisions affecting elections are subject to preclearance by the U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Department of Justice before they can take effect.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] President Lyndon Johnson's and national Democrats' support for civil rights turned many conservative whites in Virginia against the Democrats.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, many Virginians had been willing to support Republicans, at least at the national level, since the 1930s due to Franklin Roosevelt's strong support for organized labor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] While the Republican Party in most of the South tended to attract right-wing conservatives like Jesse Helms and Strom Thurmond, Virginia's GOP has tended to be more moderate by regional standards.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The state elected moderate Republican A.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Linwood Holton Jr. in 1970; Holton became the first Republican governor in the 20th century, effectively ending the influence of the Byrd Organization.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The current Virginia State Constitution was created in 1971 to replace the discriminatory one created in 1901.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Holton was succeeded by two other Republican governors: the more conservative Mills Godwin (a former Democrat) and John N.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Senator John Warner and Congressman Tom Davis also exemplified the more "moderate-conservative" tendencies of Virginia Republicans.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] From 1982 through 1994, Democrats served as governor, with Chuck Robb elected in 1981 and Gerald L.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 1989, Virginia elected Democrat Douglas Wilder governor, who served from 1990 to 1994, as Virginia's first African-American governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2001, Virginia elected Democrats Mark Warner as governor and Tim Kaine as lieutenant governor, and Kaine was elected to succeed Warner as governor in 2005.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2009, however, a Republican again returned to the governor's mansion as Bob McDonnell defeated Democrat Creigh Deeds, garnering 58.61% of the popular vote to Deeds' 41.25%.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republicans also managed to sweep all statewide races in 2009, the first time they accomplished this feat since 1997.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia voted for Republicans in nearly every presidential election from 1952 to 2004 except for the Democratic landslide in President Johnson's election in 1964.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This former streak started when Richard Nixon began the Southern Strategy, and is the longest among the former Confederate States.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia was the only such state to vote for Gerald Ford over Jimmy Carter in 1976.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Since 2008, Virginia has voted for Democrats in presidential elections, including Barack Obama; in 2016, Virginia was the only former Confederate state to vote for Hillary Clinton over Donald Trump.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 1989, Doug Wilder was the first African-American elected governor of a U.S. state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Despite Virginia's support of Republican presidential candidates and reputation as a conservative state, voters elected Democratic candidates for three consecutive gubernatorial races in the 1980s.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In addition, Democratic representatives maintained large majorities in both houses of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Many Democratic state representatives from rural and suburban districts had conservative stances on various issues.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the 1990s Virginia experienced some political realignment, electing conservative Republicans George Allen and Jim Gilmore to the governorship from 1994 until 2002.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Jim Gilmore's "no car tax" pledge was emblazoned on bumper stickers and yard signs across the state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republicans captured both houses of the General Assembly and built majorities.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Republican representatives replaced Conservative and moderate Democrats from rural and suburban areas.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Within the Republican party, more conservative officeholders supplanted the remnants of the less conservative "mountain-valley" faction of Holton, so named because many members were from the Shenandoah Valley and Southwest Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After eight years of Republican governorships, in 2001, Mark Warner, a progressive businessman, won the governorship and confronted budget difficulties related to the recession by cutting money from all state departments.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia's executive branch is limited by the fact that governors are barred from serving consecutive terms, a constitutional provision that distinguishes Virginia from any other state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] After decades of Democratic rule in the Virginia General Assembly, Republicans took control around the turn of the 21st century and promptly redistricted to protect their incumbents.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2005 Tim Kaine, Warner's lieutenant governor, won the governor's office over Jerry Kilgore and "independent Republican" state senator Russ Potts.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2006, Jim Webb narrowly defeated George Allen in the wake of the Macaca slur incident.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The electorate's reaction to Allen's gaffe demonstrated the changing sensibilities of the region's citizens; prior to that, Allen had a double-digit lead in the polls.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2007, Virginia driver fees legislation created a political uproar when residents realized that they faced $3,000 fines for certain moving violations.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] An online petition quickly gathered hundreds of thousands of signatures, spurring legislators up for re-election that November to reconsider their positions.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This was the first time that the Internet played such a dramatic role in influencing Virginia politics.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2007, the Democrats regained control of the State Senate, and narrowed the Republican majority in the House of delegates to 7 or 8 votes.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia voted for Democrat Barack Obama in 2008, after backing Republican candidates for the previous ten presidential elections.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Virginia may be considered a "swing state" for future presidential elections.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Its margin for Obama of 6.3% made it a close indicator of the national vote (a 7.2% Obama margin).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2009 general election Republican Bob McDonnell won the governorship by an 18-point margin, while Republican lieutenant governor and Attorney General candidates Bill Bolling and Ken Cuccinelli also won their respective races.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] They led statewide gains by the Republican party winning five additional seats in the House of Delegates.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2010 federal elections, Republicans picked up three U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] House seats previously held by Democrats, and proceeded to hold eight of Virginia's eleven seats, compared to three for Democrats.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the November 2018 federal elections, Democrats picked up three U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] House seats previously held by Republicans, and proceeded to hold seven of Virginia's eleven seats, compared to four for Republicans.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] From 1977 until 2013, Virginia had elected a governor of the opposite political party compared to the President of the United States of the time.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2017, Virginia returned to electing a governor of the opposite political party compared to the current President by electing Ralph Northam.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] This happened again when Glenn Youngkin was elected in 2021.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The following table lists all state and federal regular elections from 1976, along with the voter turnout.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Northern Virginia has favored Democratic candidates in recent elections.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the 2004 United States presidential election, John Kerry won Fairfax County, long a Republican stronghold, by 2.4% and generally fared better in the rest of Northern Virginia than Al Gore did in 2000.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Despite this increase, however, he still lost every other county except Arlington County in Northern Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In contrast to the changing voting trend in Northern Virginia, the majority of the rest of Virginia has been supportive of the Republican Party.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Some portions of the state like college towns and the southeastern counties in the Black Belt Region have been more likely to vote Democratic.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In 2005 and 2006, Democrats Tim Kaine (running for governor) and Jim Webb (in a race for Senator) won nearly all jurisdictions within the Northern Virginia region.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Alexandria resident Mark Warner had not won so many jurisdictions when winning the governorship in 2001.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] By contrast, Warner performed comparatively strongly in rural areas, particularly Southwest Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] His campaign stressed respect for rural cultural values (such as gun rights) and strategies for economic development.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] In the state's largest city, Virginia Beach (pop.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] 450,000), most elected officials are Republicans.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] However, most elected officials in the state's most populous county, Fairfax County (pop.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The Republican Party's strongholds are in the counties of Southwest Virginia, exurban Northern Virginia counties like Stafford, and Richmond suburbs like Hanover County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Democrats are dominant in the inner suburbs of Northern Virginia, the city of Charlottesville and its suburbs in Albemarle County, and industrial Hampton Roads cities of Norfolk, Portsmouth, Newport News, and Hampton, and also the city of Richmond.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] The three most significant "swing districts" are Loudoun and Prince William counties in Northern Virginia and Henrico County in the Richmond suburbs.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] All three of these "swing" counties voted for President George W.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/elections-in-virginia] Democrats have won formerly Republican-held seats in the General Assembly in Loudoun and Prince William counties in the 2017 and 2019 elections.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The **governor of the Commonwealth of Virginia** is the head of government of the Commonwealth of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor is head of the executive branch of the government of Virginia and is the commander-in-chief of the Virginia National Guard and Virginia Defense Force.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Three signatories of the Declaration of Independence served as governor of Virginia and three governors became president of the United States: Thomas Jefferson, James Monroe, and John Tyler.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The current officeholder is Abigail Spanberger, a member of the Democratic Party who took office on January 17, 2026.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Unlike other state governors, Virginia governors are not allowed to serve consecutive terms.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They have been barred from immediate re-election since the adoption of Virginia's second constitution, in 1830.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] However, a former governor is permitted to run for a second term in a future election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Only two governors since 1830, William Smith and Mills Godwin, have been elected to additional terms.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Smith's second term came after Virginia seceded from the Union, while Godwin became the first ever governor in American history to be elected by both major parties when the former Democrat was elected in 1973 as a Republican.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The only other governors to serve non-consecutive terms in office are Patrick Henry and James Monroe, with George William Smith serving twice as acting governor before becoming official governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] To get on the ballot for governor of Virginia, each candidate must file 10,000 signatures, including the signatures of at least 400 qualified voters from each of the 11 congressional districts in the Commonwealth.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor is the head of government in Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] At the beginning of every regular session, they must report the state of the Commonwealth to the Virginia General Assembly (both the House of Delegates and the Senate).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They must convene the legislature when two-thirds of each house calls for a special session.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor must ensure that the laws of the Commonwealth are faithfully executed by either signing, or allowing it to come into law, or vetoing, not allowing it to become law.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] They are responsible for the safety of the state, as they serve as commander-in-chief of the Virginia Militia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Established by Article V, Section 16 of the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The position of governor of Virginia dates back to the 1607 first permanent English settlement in America, at Jamestown on the north shore of the James River upstream from Hampton Roads harbor at the mouth of the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The Virginia Company of London set up a government-run by a council.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The president of the council served as a governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The council was based in London and controlled the colony from afar.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Nominally, Thomas Smith was the first president of the council, but he never left England.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Edward Maria Wingfield was the first president of the council in residence in the new province, making him the first to exercise the actual authority of governing Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The Virginia Company soon abandoned governance by council two years after the landing on May 23, 1609, and replacing it with a governor, John Smith (1580–1631).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] In 1624, the English monarchy of King James I (1566–1625, reigned 1603–1625), in the last year of his reign, of the royal House of Stuart took control from the Virginia Company and its stockholders and made Virginia a crown colony.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Governors continued to be appointed by the monarch for many years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Most often, the appointed governor would reside in England while a deputy or lieutenant governor exercised authority.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Virginia became an independent sovereign state and Commonwealth during the American Revolutionary War (1775–1783), with Patrick Henry (1736–1799, served 1776–1779 and 1786–1789) as its first governor (and also later sixth).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] From the Revolution until 1851, the governor was elected by the General Assembly of Virginia (commonwealth/state legislature).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] After 1851, in a democratic trend spreading across the Union, the state turned to popular elections for office holders.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] During the American Civil War (1861–1865), Francis Harrison Pierpont was the governor of the Union-controlled parts of the state, later of which emerged the new state in the northwest of West Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Pierpont also served as one of the provisional governors during the post-war Reconstruction era.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] These governors were appointed by the Federal government of the President and U.S.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Congress, both controlled by Radical Republicans for a decade.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] In 1874, Virginia regained its right to self-governance and elected James L.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Kemper (1823–1895), a Democrat and temporary Conservative Party member and former Confederate general as governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] After the Radical Republican appointees of the post-war Reconstruction era, Virginia would not actually elect another regular Republican as governor until A.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Cameron was elected governor under the banner of the Readjuster Party, a coalition of Republicans and populist Democrats.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Douglas Wilder became the first elected and only the second African American Governor of any U.S. state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] He served as governor from 1990 to 1994.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The only exception being in 2013 with the election of Democrat Terry McAuliffe, following the re-election of President Obama in 2012.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Tim Kaine was inaugurated on January 14, 2006.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] Due to renovations on the Capitol in Richmond, his inauguration was held in Williamsburg, making him the first governor to be inaugurated in Williamsburg since Thomas Jefferson in 1779.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The current governor of Virginia is Abigail Spanberger who was inaugurated on January 17, 2026.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/governor-of-virginia] The governor of Virginia is addressed as "The Honorable" but may occasionally be referred to as "Excellency" if ceremonially appropriate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A **governor** is an administrative leader and head of a polity or political region, in some cases, such as governors-general, as the head of a state's official representative.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Depending on the type of political region or polity, a *governor* may be either appointed or elected, and the governor's powers can vary significantly, depending on the public laws in place locally.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The adjective pertaining to a governor is **gubernatorial**, from the Latin root *gubernare*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In a federated state, the governor may serve as head of state and head of government for their regional polity, while still operating under the laws of the federation, which has its own head of state for the entire federation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Though the legal and administrative framework of provinces, each administered by a governor, was created by the Romans, the term *governor* has been a convenient term for historians to describe similar systems in antiquity.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Indeed, many regions of the pre-Roman antiquity were ultimately replaced by Roman 'standardized' provincial governments after their conquest by Rome.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Plato used the metaphor of turning the Ship of State with a rudder; the Latin word for rudder is gubernaculum.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Pharaonic times, the governors of each of the various provinces in the kingdoms of Upper and Lower Egypt (called "nomes" by the Greeks, and whose names often alluded to local patterns of religious worship) are usually known by the Greek word "nomarch," which was later used by historians.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Similarly, the term "*Haty-a"* (governor, mayor, overseer of priests, or overseer of the god's house) was referenced in inscriptions found in tombs, including those of Ankhtifi and Djefaihapi.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From the creation of the earliest Roman subject provinces, a governor was appointed each year to administer each of them.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The core function of a Roman governor was as a magistrate or judge, and the management of taxation and the public spending in their area.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Under the Republic and the early Empire, however, a governor also commanded military forces in his province.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Republican governors were all men who had served in senior magistracies (the consulate or praetorship) in Rome in the previous year, and carried related titles as governor (*proconsul* or *propraetor*).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The *legatus* sometimes would appoint a prefect (later procurator), usually a man of equestrian rank, to act as his deputy in a subregion of the larger province: the infamous character of Pontius Pilate in the Christian Gospels was a governor of this sort.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A special case was Egypt, a rich 'private' domain and vital granary, where the emperor almost inherited the theocratic status of a pharaoh.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The emperor was represented there by a governor *sui generis* styled *praefectus augustalis*, a title evoking the religious cult of the emperor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The prestigious governorships of Africa and Asia remained with the title proconsul, and the special right to refer matters directly to the emperor; the *praefectus augustalis* in Alexandria and the *comes Orientis* in Antioch also retained special titles.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Otherwise, the governors of provinces had various titles, some known as *consularis*, some as *corrector*, while others as *praeses*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Apart from Egypt and the East (*Oriens* – *viz* greater Syria), each diocese was directed by a governor known as a *vicarius*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The prefectures were directed by *praefecti praetorio* (greatly transformed in their functions from their role in the early Empire).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] This system survived with few significant changes until the collapse of the empire in the West, and in the East, the breakdown of order with the Persian and Arab invasions of the seventh century.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] At that stage, a new kind of governor emerged, the Strategos.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It was a role leading the themes which replaced provinces at this point, involving a return to the amalgamation of civil and military office which had been the practice under the Republic and the early Empire.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] While the Roman administration in the West was largely destroyed in the barbarian invasions, its model was remembered; this model became very influential through two particular vehicles: Roman law and the Christian Church.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the British Empire, a governor was originally an official appointed by the British monarch (or the cabinet) to oversee a crown colony and was the (sometimes notional) head of the colonial administration.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governors' powers varied from colony to colony, depending on its constitutional setup; while all colonies had a separate court system, the governor only had legislative power in colonies that lacked a Legislative Council or Legislative Assembly.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Today, crown colonies of the United Kingdom continue to be administered by governors who hold varying degrees of power.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Because of the different constitutional histories of the former colonies of the United Kingdom, the term *governor* now refers to officials with differing amounts of power.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Administrators, commissioners and high commissioners exercise similar powers to governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] (Note: such high commissioners are not to be confused with the high commissioners who are the equivalent of ambassadors between Commonwealth states).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Frequently the name 'Government House' is given to governors' residences.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Australia, each state has the governor as its formal representative of the sovereign, as head of the state government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It is not a political office but a ceremonial one.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each state governor is appointed by the Australian monarch on the advice of the premier, who is the political chief executive of the state government (until 1986, state governors were appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the British government).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] State governors have emergency reserve powers but these are rarely used.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The territories of Australia other than the ACT have administrators instead of governors, who are appointed formally by the governor-general.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor-general is the representative of and appointed by the King of Australia sovereign at a federal level on the advice of the prime minister of Australia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] As with the governors-general of Australia and other Commonwealth realms, state governors usually exercise their power only on the advice of a government minister.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each governor was appointed by the monarch and possessed significant powers such as the power of appointing lawmakers in the legislative council, the power to grant land, the power of veto over bills and motions, the power of pardon, etc.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] At the same time, the governor was also the head of the colonial cabinet, the chairman of the Executive Council, the president of the Legislative Council (until 1993), as well as the commander-in-chief of the British Forces in Hong Kong.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the United Kingdom's remaining overseas territories, the governor is normally a direct appointee of the British government and plays an active role in governing and lawmaking (though usually with the advice of elected local representatives).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor's chief responsibility is for the defence and external affairs of the colony.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In some minor overseas territories, instead of a governor, there is an administrator or commissioner, or the position is held *ex officio* by a High Commissioner.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Canada, there are governors at the federal and provincial levels of government who, within their jurisdictions, act as representatives of the king of Canada, who is Canada's head of state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The federal governor is the governor general of Canada, and the governor of each province is the lieutenant governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor general is appointed by the sovereign on the advice of the prime minister of Canada, whereas the lieutenant governors are appointed by the governor general on the advice of the prime minister.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The role of the governor general and of the lieutenant governors in Canada is largely ceremonial, although they do retain the authority to exercise reserve powers in exceptional circumstances.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each of the three territories is headed by a commissioner appointed by the federal Cabinet.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Unlike provincial lieutenant governors, they are not representatives of the sovereign but rather are representatives of the federal government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor-general of New Zealand is always the governor of the Ross Dependency, an Antarctic sector which is claimed by the Realm of New Zealand.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Within the United Kingdom itself, there was a position of Governor of Northern Ireland from 1922 until the suspension of the devolved Parliament of Northern Ireland in 1973.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From the 16th century until 1995, there was a governor of the Isle of Wight, part of England.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Since the reign of Henry VIII, the monarch has borne the title of Supreme Governor of the Church of England.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] European powers other than the United Kingdom, with colonies in Asia, Africa and elsewhere, gave their top representatives in their colonies the title of governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Those representatives could be from chartered companies that ruled the colonies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In some of these colonies, there are still officials called governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the Russian Empire, the governorate (guberniya) and governorate-general were the main units of territorial and administrative subdivision since the reforms of Peter the Great.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] These were governed by a governor and governor-general respectively.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A special case was the Chinese Eastern Railway Zone, which was governed as a concession granted by Imperial China to the Russian 'Chinese Eastern Railway Society' (in Russian *Obshchestvo Kitayskoy Vostochnoy Zheleznoy Dorogi*; established on 17 December 1896 in St.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The post continued to function despite various political changes until after World War II.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Some of the administrative subdivisions of Russia are headed by governors, while others are headed by presidents or heads of administration.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1991 to 2005, they were elected by popular vote and from 2005 to 2012, they were appointed by the federal president and confirmed by the province's legislature.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] After the debate, conducted by State Duma in April 2012, the direct elections of governors were expected to be restored.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A Landeshauptmann (German for "state captain" or "state governor", literally 'country headman'; plural *Landeshauptleute* or *Landeshauptmänner* as in Styria till 1861; *Landeshauptfrau* is the female form) is an official title in German for certain political offices equivalent to a governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] It has historical uses, both administrative and colonial, and is now used in federal Austria and in South Tyrol, a majority German-speaking province of Italy adjacent to Tyrol.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] During the Ancien Régime in France, the representative of the king in his provinces and cities was the ***gouverneur***.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Royal officers were chosen from the highest nobility, and provincial and city governors (oversight of provinces and cities was frequently combined) were predominantly military positions in charge of defense and policing.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Provincial governors – also called "lieutenant generals" – also had the ability to convoke provincial parlements, provincial estates and municipal bodies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The title "gouverneur" first appeared under Charles VI.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The ordinance of Blois of 1579 reduced their number to 12, but an ordinance of 1779 increased their number to 39 (18 first-class governors, 21 second-class governors).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Although in principle, they were the king's representatives and their charges could be revoked at the king's will, some governors had installed themselves and their heirs as a provincial dynasty.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Until 1933, the term *Landeshauptmann* (state governor) was used in Prussia for the head of government of a province, In the modern-day states of Germany, the counterpart to *Landeshauptmann* is the *Ministerpräsident* (minister-president).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the present German states of Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, Hesse, and North Rhine-Westphalia there are – and earlier in more German states there were – sub-state administrative regions called in German: *Regierungsbezirk*, which is sometimes translated into English as governorate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Thus its respective head, in German: *Regierungspräsident*, is also translated as governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Ioannis Kapodistrias was the first (and, with the exception of the short tenure of his younger brother Augustinos Kapodistrias, the only) head of state of Greece to bear the title of governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the People's Republic of China, the title *Governor* (Chinese: 省长; pinyin: *shěngzhǎng*) refers to the highest ranking executive of a provincial government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is usually placed second in the provincial power hierarchy, below the secretary of the provincial Chinese Communist Party (CCP) committee (省委书记), who serves as the highest ranking party official in the province.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Governors are elected by the provincial congresses and approved by the provincial party chief.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] All governors are not locals in the provinces which they govern.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The title can be also used while referring to a county governor (县长).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In India, each state has a ceremonial governor appointed by the president of India.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] These governors are different from the governors who controlled the British-controlled portions of the Indian Empire (as opposed to the princely states) prior to 1947.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A governor is the head of a state in India.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Generally, a governor is appointed for each state, but after the 7th Constitutional Amendment, of 1956, one governor can be appointed for more than one state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Indonesia, the title *gubernur* refers to the highest-ranking executive of a provincial government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor and the vice governor are elected by a direct vote from the people as a couple candidate, so the governor is responsible to the provincial residents.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor has a term of five years to work in office and can be re-elected for another single period.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In case of death, disability, or resignation, the vice governor would stand in as acting governor for some time before being inaugurated as the permanent governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The elected governor is inaugurated by the president, or by the Indonesian minister of home affairs on behalf of the president.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In addition, the governor is the representative of the central government in the province and is responsible to the president.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor's authority is regulated within Law (Indonesian: *Undang-undang*) No.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] 32/2004 and Governmental Ordinance (Indonesian: *Peraturan Pemerintah*) No.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Principally, the governor has the tasks and the authorities to lead governmental services in the province, based upon the policies that have been made together with the provincial parliament.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is not the superordinate of regents or mayors, but only guides supervises, and coordinates the works of city/municipal and regency governments.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In other parts, municipal and regency governments have the right to manage each governance affairs based on the autonomy principle and assistantship duties.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Japan, the title *Governor* (知事, *chiji*) refers to the highest ranking executive of a prefectural government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected by a direct vote from the people and had a fixed term of four years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] There is no restriction on the number of terms a person may serve as governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor holds considerable power within the prefecture, including the ability to veto ordinances that have been passed by the prefecture assembly, as well as control of the prefecture's budget and the power to dissolve the prefecture assembly.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor can be subjected to a recall referendum.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A total of one to four vice governors are appointed by the governor with the approval of the assembly.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the case of the governor's death, disability, or resignation, a vice governor would stand in as governor or acting governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] See List of governors of Japan for a list of the current governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Each of these states has a separate head of government called the *Ketua Menteri* or chief minister.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The four Yang di-Pertua Negeri are members of the Conference of Rulers; however, they cannot participate in the election of the Yang di-Pertuan Agong, discussions related to the privileges of the Malay rulers and matters concerning the observance of Islam.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Pakistan, each of the four provinces has a governor who is appointed by the president.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is the representative of the federal in their province and is the ceremonial head of the province whereas the chief minister is the head of the provincial government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor exercises powers similar to the president's, in their respective province.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the Philippines, the highest-ranking executive of a province is styled *Governor* (*Gobernador* or *Punong Lalawigan* in Filipino).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The governor is elected by direct vote of the people with a fixed term of three years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] A governor can serve only up to a maximum of three consecutive terms.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may, however, be suspended by either the ombudsman or the President through the secretary of the interior and local government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may be removed by the President if found guilty of an administrative case or a criminal act during his tenure.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] He may be subjected to a recall vote, but unlike a referendum, the voters elect the governor of their choice.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In case of death, disability, resignation, forced removal, or suspension, the vice governor, elected separately in the same election for governor, succeeds as governor, or acting governor, as the case may be.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] During both the Spanish and American colonial periods, as well as during the Japanese occupation of World War II, the chief executive of the Philippines was the Governor-general of the Philippines.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The highest ranking executive of the former Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao was called *regional governor,* elected for a term of three years and if vacating office, replaced by a regional vice-governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Bangsamoro, its replacement, has the *Wa'lī* (Arabic for "governor") as ceremonial head of the region, elected by parliament for a six-year term.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The provincial councils of the nine provinces of Sri Lanka are headed by governors, as representatives of the president.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1948, in Ceylon (former name for Sri Lanka), the governor of Ceylon was the head of the British colony.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Thailand, the title *Governor* (ผู้ว่าราชการ *Phuwa Ratcha Gaan* in Thai) refers to the administrator of each Thai province, who is appointed by the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The only exception is the specially governed district of Bangkok, whose governor is elected by its population.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Mexico, *governor* refers to the elected leader of each of the nation's thirty-one Free and Sovereign States with the official Spanish title being *Gobernador*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Mexican governors are directly elected by the citizens of each state for a six-year term and cannot be re-elected.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the United States, the title "Governor" refers to the head of each state or insular territory.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Governors retain sovereign power over executive and judiciary, are subordinate to the president of the United States and laws provided by the enumerated powers section of the federal constitution, and serve as the political and ceremonial head of the state.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Nearly three-fourths of the states (36) hold gubernatorial elections in the same years as midterm elections (two years offset from presidential elections).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Eleven states hold them in the same years as presidential elections (Vermont and New Hampshire hold elections every two years in every even-numbered year), while the remaining five hold them in odd-numbered years (two in the year after a presidential election, three in the year before).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In colonial North America, governors were chosen in a variety of ways, depending on how the colony was organized.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the crown colonies of Great Britain, France, and Spain, the governor was chosen by the ruling monarch of the colonizing power or his designees; in British colonies, the Board of Trade was often the primary decision maker.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Colonies based on a corporate charter, such as the Connecticut Colony and the Massachusetts Bay Colony, elected their own governors based on rules spelt out in the charter or other colonial legislation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In proprietary colonies, such as the Province of Carolina before it became a crown colony (and was divided into North and South), governors were chosen by the Lords Proprietor who controlled the colony.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In the early years of the American Revolutionary War, eleven of the Thirteen Colonies evicted (with varying levels of violence) royal and proprietary governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] The other two colonies (Connecticut and Rhode Island) had corporate charters; Connecticut Governor Jonathan Trumbull was governor before and during the war period, while in Rhode Island, Governor Joseph Wanton was removed from office in 1775 for failing to support the rebel war effort.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Before achieving statehood, many of the fifty states were territories.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Administered by the federal government, they had governors who were appointed by the president and confirmed by the Senate rather than elected by the resident population.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] In Papua New Guinea, the leaders of the provinces have been known as governors since August 1995.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Many of the South American republics (such as Chile and Argentina) have provinces or states run by elected governors, with offices similar in nature to U.S. state governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] Until the 1930 Revolution, the heads of the Brazilian Provinces, now called States, were styled as (provincial/state) presidents (*presidentes*).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1930 to 1945, they were styled either governors (*governadores*) or, when appointed by the federal government, intervenors (*interventores*).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/gubernatorial-election] From 1945 on, they have only been called governors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] A native of Hanover County, Virginia, Henry was primarily educated at home.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] After an unsuccessful venture running a store, as well as assisting his father-in-law at Hanover Tavern, he became a lawyer through self-study.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Beginning his practice in 1760, Henry soon became prominent through his victory in the Parson's Cause against the Anglican clergy.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He was elected to the Virginia House of Burgesses, where he quickly became notable for his inflammatory rhetoric against the Stamp Act of 1765.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1774, Henry served as a delegate to the First Continental Congress where he signed the Petition to the King, which he helped to draft, and the Continental Association.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He gained further popularity among the people of Virginia, both through his oratory at the convention and by marching troops towards the colonial capital of Williamsburg after the Gunpowder Incident until the munitions seized by the royal government were paid for.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry urged independence, and when the Fifth Virginia Convention endorsed this in 1776, he served on the committee charged with drafting the Virginia Declaration of Rights and the original Virginia Constitution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was promptly elected governor under the new charter and served a total of five one-year terms.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] After leaving the governorship in 1779, Henry served in the Virginia House of Delegates until he began his last two terms as governor in 1784.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The actions of the national government under the Articles of Confederation made Henry fear a strong federal government, and he declined appointment as a delegate to the 1787 Constitutional Convention.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He actively opposed the ratification of the United States Constitution, both fearing a powerful central government and because there was as yet no Bill of Rights.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He returned to the practice of law in his final years, declining several offices under the federal government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] A slaveholder throughout his adult life, he hoped to see the institution end but had no plan beyond ending the importation of slaves.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry is remembered for his oratory and as an enthusiastic promoter of the fight for independence.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was born on the family farm, Studley, in Hanover County in the Colony of Virginia, on May 29, 1736.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] His father was John Henry, an immigrant from Aberdeenshire, Scotland, who had attended King's College, University of Aberdeen, before emigrating to Virginia in the 1720s.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Settling in Hanover County in about 1732, John Henry married Sarah Winston Syme, a wealthy widow from a prominent local family of English ancestry.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Patrick Henry shared his name with his uncle, an Anglican minister, and until the elder Patrick's death in 1777 often went as Patrick Henry Jr.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry attended a local school until about the age of 10.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] There was no academy in Hanover County, and he was tutored at home by his father.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The young Henry engaged in the typical recreations of the times, such as music and dancing, and was particularly fond of hunting.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Since the family's stock, considerable lands, and slaves would pass to his older half-brother John Syme Jr., due to the custom of primogeniture, Henry needed to make his own way in the world.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] At age 15, he became a clerk for a local merchant and a year later opened a store with his older brother William.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] His sisters were pioneer and writer Annie Henry Christian and Elizabeth Henry Campbell Russell, a Methodist lay leader.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The religious revival known as the First Great Awakening reached Virginia when Henry was a child.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] His father was staunchly Anglican, but his mother often took him to hear Presbyterian preachers.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although Henry remained a lifelong Anglican communicant, ministers such as Samuel Davies taught him that it is not enough to save one's own soul, but one should help to save society.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He also learned that oratory should reach the heart, not just persuade based on reason.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] His oratorical technique would follow that of these preachers, seeking to reach the people by speaking to them in their own language.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Religion played a key role in Henry's life; his father and namesake uncle were both devout and were both major influences in his life.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Nevertheless, he was uncomfortable with the role of the Anglican Church as the established religion in Virginia, and he fought for religious liberty throughout his career.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1754, Henry married Sarah Shelton, reportedly in the parlor of her family house, Rural Plains (which also became known as Shelton House).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As a wedding gift, her father gave the couple six slaves and the 300-acre (1.2 km2) Pine Slash Farm near Mechanicsville.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Pine Slash was exhausted from earlier cultivations, and Henry worked with the slaves to clear fresh fields.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The latter half of the 1750s were years of drought in Virginia, and after the main house burned down, Henry gave up and moved to the Hanover Tavern, owned by Sarah's father.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry often served as host at Hanover Tavern as part of his duties and entertained the guests by playing the fiddle.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Among those who stayed there during this time was Thomas Jefferson, aged 17, en route to his studies at the College of William & Mary, and who later wrote that he became well acquainted with Henry then, despite their age difference of six years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Jefferson in 1824 told Daniel Webster, "Patrick Henry was originally a bar-keeper", a characterization that Henry's biographers have found to be unfair; that his position was more general than that, and that the main business of Hanover Tavern was serving travelers, not alcohol.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] William Wirt, Henry's earliest biographer, rejects Jefferson's suggestion that Henry's profession was a bartender but notes it would have been "very natural in Mr.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry's situation" to do what was necessary to ensure that guests were properly seen to.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] While at Hanover Tavern, Henry found time to study the law.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] How long he did so is unclear; he later said it was as little as a month.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On the advice of a local lawyer, Henry in 1760 applied for a lawyer's license, appearing before the examiners—prominent attorneys in the colonial capital of Williamsburg.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The examiners were impressed by Henry's mind even though his knowledge of legal procedures was scant.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He passed in April 1760, and he thereafter opened a practice, appearing in the courts of Hanover and nearby counties.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The droughts of the 1750s had led to a rise in the price of tobacco.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Hard currency was scarce in Virginia, and salaries in the colony were often expressed in terms of pounds of tobacco.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] These payees included public officials, including Anglican clergy—Anglicanism was Virginia's established church—and several ministers petitioned the Board of Trade in London to overrule the Burgesses, which it did.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Five clergymen then brought suit for back pay, cases known as the Parson's Cause; of them, only the Reverend James Maury was successful, and a jury was to be empaneled in Hanover County on December 1, 1763, to fix damages.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was engaged as counsel by Maury's parish vestry for this hearing.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Patrick Henry's father, Colonel John Henry, was the presiding judge.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] After the evidence was presented proving the facts at issue, Maury's counsel gave a speech in praise of the clergy, many of whom were in attendance.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry responded with a one-hour speech, ignoring the question of damages, but which focused on the unconstitutionality of the veto of the Two Penny Act by the king's government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry deemed any king who annulled good laws, such as the Two Penny Act, as a "tyrant" who "forfeits all right to his subjects' obedience", and the clergy, by challenging an impartial law designed to bring economic relief, had shown themselves to be "enemies of the community".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The opposing counsel accused Henry of treason, and some took up that cry, but Henry continued, and the judge did nothing to stop him.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry urged the jury to make an example of Maury, for the benefit of any who might seek to imitate him and suggested the jury return damages of one farthing.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The jury was out for only moments and fixed damages at one penny.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In the wake of the Parson's Cause, Henry began to gain a following in backwoods Virginia because of his oratory defending the liberties of the common people and thanks to his friendly manner.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He boosted his standing further in 1764 by representing Nathaniel West Dandridge, elected for Hanover County, in an election contest before the Burgesses.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Dandridge was alleged to have bribed voters with drink, a practice common but illegal.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry is said to have made a brilliant speech in defense of the rights of voters, but the text does not survive.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry lost the case but met influential members on the Committee of Privileges and Elections, such as Richard Henry Lee, Peyton Randolph and George Wythe.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1765, William Johnson, the brother of Thomas Johnson (who had been one of Henry's clients in the Parson's Cause), resigned as burgess for Louisa County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As Henry owned land in the county (acquired from his father to settle a loan), he was eligible to be a candidate, and he won the seat in May 1765.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He left immediately for Williamsburg as the session had already begun.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The expense of the Seven Years' War (called the French and Indian War in North America) (1756–1763) had nearly doubled Britain's national debt, and as much of the war had taken place in and around North America, the British government looked for ways of directly taxing the American colonies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The 1765 Stamp Act was both a means of raising revenue and one of asserting authority over the colonies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Burgesses instructed their agent in London, Edward Montague, to oppose the measure, and other colonial legislatures similarly instructed their representatives.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Considerable debate began over the proposed measure, and in Virginia pamphleteers developed arguments Henry had made in the Parson's Cause.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Patrick Henry was sworn into a sleepy session of the legislature on May 20; many of the members had left town.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On about May 28, a ship arrived with an urgent letter from Montague: the Stamp Act had passed.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On May 29, Henry introduced the Virginia Stamp Act Resolves.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The first two resolutions affirmed that the colonists had the same rights and privileges as Britons; the next two stated that taxation should be exacted only by one's representatives.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The fifth was the most provocative, as it named the Virginia legislature, the General Assembly, as the representatives of Virginia empowered to tax.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Two other resolutions were offered, though their authorship is uncertain.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Edmund and Helen Morgan, in their account of the Stamp Act crisis, suggest that Henry saw the Stamp Act as both a threat to Virginians' rights and an opportunity to advance himself politically.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] There are no verbatim transcriptions of Henry's speech in opposition to the Stamp Act.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Texts are reconstructions, for the most part based on recollections decades later, by which time both the speech and Henry had become famous.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] For example, Jefferson, still in his studies at the nearby College of William & Mary, recalled the splendor of Henry's oratory.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] No attempt was made to reconstruct Henry's words until 1790, when James Madison wrote to former burgess Edmund Pendleton, but Madison learned that Pendleton had not been present; a second attempt did not occur until Wirt began work on his biography of Henry in 1805.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As Henry had seemingly called for the killing of King George III, there were cries of "Treason!" in the chamber, including by Speaker John Robinson.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] (father of the future president), who was standing with Jefferson as they watched the session, called this one of "the trying moments which is decisive of character", and both recalled that Henry did not waver: "If this be treason, make the most of it!".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Burgesses adopted the first five resolutions—the two others, which denied the right of any other body but the General Assembly to tax Virginians and which branded anyone who stated that Parliament had that right an enemy of the colony, were not passed.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] According to the Morgans, the passed resolutions differed little from language in petitions sent by the Burgesses to London in 1764, and the opposition to Henry may have been in part because he was an upstart in Virginia politics.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On May 31, with Henry absent and likely returning home, the Burgesses expunged the fifth resolution, and Royal Governor Francis Fauquier refused to allow any of them to be printed in the official newspaper, the *Virginia Gazette*.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] With the official texts of the passed resolutions denied them, newspapers in the colonies and in Britain printed all seven resolutions, all of them presented as the resolves of the influential Colony of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The resolutions, more radical as a group than what was actually passed, reached Britain by mid-August, the first American reaction to the passage of the Stamp Act.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In North America, they galvanized opposition to the Stamp Act and made Virginia the leader in opposition to Parliament's action.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Fauquier dissolved the Burgesses on June 1, 1765, hoping new elections would purge the radicals, but this proved not to be the case as conservative leaders were instead voted out.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The governor did not call the Burgesses into session until November 1766, by which time the Stamp Act had been repealed by Parliament, preventing Virginia from sending delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry's role in the active resistance that took place in Virginia against the Stamp Act is uncertain.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although the lack of a legislative session sidelined Henry during the crisis, it also undermined the established leaders of the chamber, who remained scattered through the colony with little opportunity to confer as the public rage for change grew hotter.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] When the Burgesses eventually convened, Henry sometimes opposed the colonial leaders but united with them against British policies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In the late 1760s and early 1770s, Henry spent more time concentrating on his personal affairs, though he advanced in standing within the Burgesses serving on powerful committees.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Henry family moved to a new house on his Louisa County property, probably in late 1765, and lived there until 1769 when he returned to Hanover County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] His law practice remained strong until the courts under royal authority closed in 1774.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Jefferson later complained that Henry was lazy and ignorant in the practice of the law, his sole talent trying cases before juries, and accused Henry of charging criminal defendants high fees to get them acquitted.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Norine Dickson Campbell, in her biography of Henry, found Jefferson's comments unfounded, noting that Henry's rates were moderate for the time and citing earlier historians as to Henry's competence.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Jefferson's comments came years after the two, once friends, quarreled.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1769, Henry was admitted to practice before the General Court of Virginia in Williamsburg, a venue more prestigious than the county courts.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry invested some of his earnings in frontier lands, in what is now the western part of Virginia, as well as in what became present-day West Virginia and Kentucky.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He claimed ownership though many of them were controlled by the Native Americans, and he sought to get the colonial (and, later, state) government to recognize his claims.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This was common among Virginia's leading citizens, such as George Washington.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry foresaw the potential of the Ohio Valley and was involved in schemes to found settlements.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Income from land deals in 1771 enabled him to buy Scotchtown, a large plantation in Hanover County, which he purchased from John Payne, the father of Dolley Madison—she lived there for a brief time as a child.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Scotchtown, with 16 rooms, was one of the largest mansions in Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was a lifelong slaveholder from the time of his marriage at age 18.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] I am drawn along by the general inconvenience of living here without them.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] I will not, I cannot justify it." But the number of slaves he owned increased over time and as a result of his second marriage in 1777, so that at his death in 1799, he owned 67 slaves.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1778, Henry and other planters, believing there to be a surplus of slave labor in Virginia, easily brought the transatlantic importation of new enslaved Africans to an end.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The planters supported the effort to limit slave imports for their own economic reasons and for fear of slave rebellions, but they did not seek abolition of slaves already in Virginia, although moving towards abolition was said to be a reason for passing the act.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] With a surplus of slaves and the ability to import more African slaves cut off, Virginia later became a source of slaves sold south in the coastwise slave trade.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In 1773, Henry came into conflict with the royal governor, John Murray, 4th Earl of Dunmore.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The governor, appointed in 1771, had sent British soldiers to Pittsylvania County to aid in apprehending a gang of counterfeiters.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Once captured, they were immediately taken to Williamsburg for trial before the General Court, ignoring precedent that judicial proceedings should begin in the county where the offense took place or where the suspect had been captured.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This was a sensitive matter especially because of the recent *Gaspee* Affair in Rhode Island, in which the British sought to capture and transport overseas for trial those who had burned a British ship.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Burgesses wanted to rebuke Dunmore for his actions, and Henry was part of a committee of eight that drafted a resolution thanking the governor for the capture of the gang but affirming that using the "usual mode" of criminal procedure protected both the guilty and the innocent.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] They also penned a plan, adopted by the Burgesses, for a committee of correspondence to communicate with leaders in other colonies to inform and coordinate with each other.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although Henry had by this time come to believe that conflict with Great Britain, and independence, were inevitable, he had no strategy for this.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Burgesses were sitting when in 1774, word came that Parliament had voted to close the port of Boston in retaliation for the Boston Tea Party, and several burgesses, including Henry, convened at the Raleigh Tavern to formulate a response.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] According to George Mason, a former burgess from Fairfax County who joined the committee in the work, Henry took the lead.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Mason and Henry formed a close political relationship that lasted until Mason's death in 1792.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The resolution that Henry's committee produced set June 1, 1774, the date upon which the Port of Boston was to be closed, as a day of fasting and prayer.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] It passed the Burgesses, but Dunmore dissolved the body.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Undeterred, the former legislators met at the Raleigh Tavern and reconstituted themselves as a convention to meet again in August, after there was time for county meetings to show local sentiment.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] They also called for a boycott of tea and other products.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The five Virginia Conventions (1774–1776) would guide the Colony of Virginia to independence as royal authority came to an end.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Their work was advanced by many resolutions of county meetings, denying the authority of Parliament over the colonies and calling for a boycott of imports.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The first convention met in Williamsburg in the chamber of the Burgesses beginning on August 1; Dunmore was absent from the capital fighting the Native Americans and could not interfere.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Divided between those who wanted separation from Britain and those who still hoped for some accommodation, it met for a week; one major decision was the election of delegates to a Continental Congress in Philadelphia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was chosen as one of seven delegates, tying for second place with Washington, burgess for Fairfax County, both receiving three votes less than Randolph.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As Washington's estate, Mount Vernon, lay on the way from Scotchtown to Philadelphia, he invited Henry to stop there and to ride to Philadelphia with him.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry and Pendleton, another Virginia delegate to the Congress and a political rival of Henry's, accepted the invitation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Delegates and prominent Philadelphians took an intense interest in the Virginians, who had taken the lead in resistance to Britain but whom few in the other colonies had met.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This was Henry's first stay in the North aside from a brief business trip to New York in 1770, but he found that his actions were well known.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The sessions began on September 5, 1774, at Carpenters' Hall.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Silas Deane of Connecticut described Henry as "the compleatest speaker I ever heard ... but in a Letter I can give You no Idea of the Music of his Voice, or the highwrought, yet Natural elegance of his Stile, or Manner".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The secretary of the Congress, Charles Thomson, wrote that when Henry rose, he had expected little from a man dressed as plainly as a rural minister.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] "But as he proceeded, [he] evinced such [an] unusual force of argument, and such novel and impassioned eloquence as soon electrified the whole house.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Then the excited inquiry passed from man to man ...
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was involved in the first dispute within the Congress on whether each colony should have an equal vote, taking the position that there should be proportional representation giving the larger colonies a greater voice.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He argued that colonial borders must be swept away in the need for Americans to unify and create a government to fill the void left with the end of British authority, "Fleets and armies and the present state of things shew that Government is dissolved.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Where are your landmarks? your boundaries of colonies?
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The distinctions between Virginians, Pennsylvanians, New Yorkers, and New Englanders are no more.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] I am not a Virginian, but an American." Henry lost the argument, and his theatrics made Congress's leaders afraid he would be unpredictable if placed on the lead committee charged with composing a statement regarding colonial rights.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Instead, he was put on the next most important committee, one inquiring into commercial regulation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In the end, though, neither committee produced much of importance.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry believed the purpose of the Congress should be to mobilize public opinion towards war.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In this, he found common cause with John Adams and Samuel Adams of Massachusetts, but not all were of that opinion.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] According to Tate, Henry "turned out not to be an especially influential member of the body".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Congress decided on a petition to the king; Henry prepared two drafts, but neither proved satisfactory.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] When Congress on October 26 approved a draft prepared by John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, who had consulted with Henry and also Richard Henry Lee, Henry had already departed for home, and Lee signed on his behalf.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] After the birth of their sixth child in 1771, Patrick's wife Sarah Shelton Henry began to exhibit symptoms of mental illness, and one reason for the move from Louisa County to Scotchtown was so they could be near family members.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry's biographer, Jon Kukla believes she was the victim of postpartum psychosis, for which there was no treatment.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] At times, she was restrained in a form of straitjacket.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although Virginia had opened the first public mental facility in North America in 1773, Henry decided that she was better off at Scotchtown and prepared a large apartment for her there.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] She died in 1775, after which Henry avoided all objects that reminded him of her and sold Scotchtown in 1777.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Hanover County elected Henry as a delegate to the Second Virginia Convention, which convened at St.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] John's Episcopal Church in the town of Richmond on March 20, 1775.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Richmond was selected as better protected from royal authority.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The convention debated whether Virginia should adopt language from a petition by the planters of the Colony of Jamaica.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This document contained complaints about British actions but admitted the king could veto colonial legislation, and it urged reconciliation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry offered amendments to raise a militia independent of royal authority in terms that recognized that conflict with Britain was inevitable, sparking the opposition of moderates.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As he concluded, Henry plunged an ivory paper cutter towards his chest in imitation of the Roman patriot Cato the Younger.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry's speech carried the day, and the convention adopted his amendments.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Still, they passed only narrowly, as many delegates were uncertain where the resistance urged by Henry and other radicals would lead, and few counties formed independent militia companies at the urging of the convention.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The text of Henry's speech first appeared in print in Wirt's 1817 biography, published 18 years after Patrick Henry's death.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Wirt corresponded with men who had heard the speech and others who were acquainted with people who were there at the time.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] All agreed that the speech had produced a profound effect, but it seems that only one person attempted to render an actual text.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] George Tucker, who had been present for the speech, gave Wirt his recollections and Wirt wrote back stating that "I have taken almost entirely Mr.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry's speech in the Convention of '75 from you, as well as your description of its effect on your verbatim." The original letter with Tucker's remembrances has been lost.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] For 160 years Wirt's account was taken at face value.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In the 1970s, historians began to question the authenticity of Wirt's reconstruction.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Tucker's account was based upon recollections and not notes, several decades after the speech; he wrote, "In vain should I attempt to give any idea of his speech".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Scholars have argued to what extent the speech we know is the work of Wirt or Tucker.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On April 21, 1775, Dunmore had British marines under his command seize gunpowder from the magazine in Williamsburg and take it to a naval ship.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The gunpowder belonged to the government, to be issued in case of need, such as a slave uprising.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Dunmore's actions outraged many Virginians.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry had departed for Philadelphia, having been elected a delegate to the Second Continental Congress, but a messenger caught up with him before he left Hanover County, and he returned to take command of the local militia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Seeking the restoration of the powder, or that the colonists be compensated for it, on May 2, Henry led his troops towards Williamsburg with, as Dunmore wrote, "all the Appearances of actual War".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] By this time, word of the Battles of Lexington and Concord had arrived, and many Virginians believed that war with Britain had begun.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As Henry insisted the colonists be compensated, a member of the Governor's Council agreed to pay the value of the powder by bill of exchange.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Not all approved; Henry's march appalled some moderates who feared he might provoke a conflict in which Virginia stood alone against Britain's might.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] They also saw him as a threat to the sanctity of property, for anyone's might be taken by Henry and his troops.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As popular support for independence grew, opponents either joined in the movement or decided it was wiser to remain silent.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry belatedly arrived at the Congress on May 18, 1775.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Jefferson later stated that Henry played only a supporting role, and though there is not a complete record, the fact that he was not written of as having an impact appears to confirm that.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The Congress appointed Washington as head of American forces, an appointment that Henry supported.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] At the end of the session, in August, Henry left Philadelphia for Virginia and would never again hold office outside its borders.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] While Henry was returning, the Third Virginia Convention in August commissioned him as colonel of the 1st Virginia Regiment, and he took up the appointment later that month.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although Henry had little military experience, this was not considered a major drawback at the time, and he was held to have distinguished himself in the march on Williamsburg.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] General Washington, though, felt that the convention had "made a Capital mistake when they took Henry out of the Senate to place him in the Field".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In September, Virginia's Committee of Safety placed Henry in charge of all Virginia's forces.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Despite the high title, Henry was placed under tight civilian control, and to an extent the willingness of moderates to go along with the appointment reflected a view that in that position, the volatile Henry would be contained.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry moved to organize his regiment and had no difficulty recruiting men.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In November 1775, Dunmore, who though he had abandoned Williamsburg still held Norfolk, issued a proclamation offering freedom to any black slave or indentured servant willing and able to serve in his forces, which already included several hundred former slaves.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry wrote to all county lieutenants, stating that the proclamation "is fatal to the publick Safety" and urging an "unremitting Attention to the Government of the SLAVES may, I hope, counteract this dangerous Attempt.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry saw no action himself, and there were murmurs in the convention against his command; some feared he was too radical to be an effective military leader.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In February 1776, Virginia's forces were reorganized as they were placed under Continental command.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was to retain his rank of colonel but was placed under a former subordinate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry refused and left the army; his troops were outraged by the slight to him and considered leaving service, but he calmed the situation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry did not sit in the Fourth Virginia Convention which met in December 1775, as he was ineligible because of his military commission.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Once he was again a civilian, the freeholders of Hanover County in April 1776 elected him to the fifth convention, to meet the following month.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Most delegates were for independence but were divided on how and when to declare it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry introduced a resolution declaring Virginia independent and urging the Congress to declare all the colonies free.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] When he at last spoke, according to clergyman Edmund Randolph, Henry "appeared in an element for which he was born.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] To cut the knot, which calm prudence was puzzled to untie, was worthy of the magnificence of his genius.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] As well as declaring Virginia independent, the resolution instructed the state's delegates in Congress to press for American independence, which they would, with Lee introducing the motion and Jefferson penning the Declaration.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The convention then proceeded to consider a constitution for Virginia's government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was appointed to a committee under the leadership of Archibald Cary.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Much of the work fell to the final appointee to the committee, George Mason of Fairfax County, who did not arrive in Williamsburg until May 18, delayed by illness.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Mason first drafted a Declaration of Rights; it was discussed in the Cary Committee on May 25.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Mason's draft, more than the final declaration, would be highly influential, used by Jefferson in writing the Declaration of Independence and by writers of many 18th- and 19th-century state constitutions.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] When the draft was debated, Henry, at the request of a young delegate from Orange County, James Madison, produced an amendment changing Mason's call for religious tolerance to one requiring full freedom of religion.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This was seen as a threat to Virginia's established religion, Anglicanism, and did not pass.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Madison reworked it and had another delegate introduce it, likely Randolph, and it passed.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Mason's draft called for a ban on bills of attainder.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry got it removed by telling the delegates that some high offender might be reached by no other means.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The convention approved the Declaration of Rights on June 12.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] But it was Mason's plan for the government of Virginia which dominated, with much power given to the Virginia House of Delegates, the lower house of the legislature.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The House of Delegates and the Senate of Virginia together formed the General Assembly, as the Virginia legislature is known.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Under the 1776 constitution, the governor, elected by the two houses of the legislature, was not even given the power to veto legislation and was required to act with the approval of the Governor's Council on important matters.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry opposed the weakness of the governor, feeling it was risky at a time of war to have the executive so weak, but his views did not prevail.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He had reason to rue the office's lack of power, as on June 29, 1776, the convention elected him as Virginia's first post-independence governor, by 60 votes to 45 for Thomas Nelson Jr.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The election of Henry, at that time Virginia's most popular politician, helped assure acceptance of the new authorities but also placed him in a figurehead position, removed from the true power in the new government, the House of Delegates.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was taken ill almost immediately upon being sworn in as governor on July 5 and recuperated at Scotchtown.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He returned to Williamsburg in September and corresponded with General Washington about the military situation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Washington, who was less effective because of the inadequacies of his troops, complained about the state militias, feeling a Continental Army committed for the duration of the war was needed.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry helped recruit new troops for Washington, but his efforts were hampered by several issues, including the weakness of Henry's office.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In March 1777, Henry wrote to Washington seeking permission to recruit soldiers for terms of up to eight months.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Washington's anger in his response that such troops were not useful caused Henry to drop the matter, stating that he deferred to Washington's experience in military matters.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Recruiting remained a problem; many Virginians were willing to be members of the county militia but did not want to join the Continental Army lest they be sent out of state or exposed to disease.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Desertion was also a problem Henry labored to solve with limited success; many Virginians had been induced to enlist with promises they would not be sent outside the state or local area, and they left when orders came to march.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was elected to a second one-year term without opposition and took the oath on July 2, 1777.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] On October 9 at Scotchtown, he married Dorothea Dandridge, daughter of his old client, Nathaniel West Dandridge of Hanover County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This made him closer kin to Washington, as Nathaniel Dandridge was Martha Washington's uncle.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] To add to the six children he had by Sarah Henry, he would have eleven more by Dorothea, though two by the second marriage died very young.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] She brought 12 slaves with her, adding to the 30 Patrick Henry already had.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] He sold Scotchtown in 1777 and moved to Leatherwood Plantation in Henry County, which the General Assembly had just created and named for him.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] When Washington and his troops encamped at Valley Forge in the winter of 1777–78, Henry arranged for livestock and other food to be sent to their relief.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] There was discontent against Washington, who was not seen by some as a successful general, and this resulted in the so-called Conway Cabal.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Benjamin Rush of Philadelphia, one of those unenthusiastic about Washington, sent the governor an unsigned letter, discussing machinations against the general.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry immediately sent Washington the letter, and though it is uncertain if Henry recognized Rush's handwriting, Washington did, tipping him off to the conspiracy.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In an effort to secure Virginia's vast claims in the West (to the Mississippi River and north to present-day Minnesota) against British and Native American forces, Henry in December 1777 sent George Rogers Clark on an expedition against Kaskaskia, site of a British and French settlement.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] This part of Clark's mission was secret; his public orders merely stated he was to raise a militia and go to Kentucky (then part of Virginia).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Clark captured Kaskaskia in July 1778 and remained north of the Ohio River for the remainder of Henry's governorship.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Although the expedition did not turn out as well as hoped, Henry trumpeted its successes, but after he left the governorship in 1779 and was elected to the House of Delegates, he became a foe of Clark.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Henry was elected to a third term on May 29, 1778, again without opposition.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] Jefferson led the committee of notables sent to inform him of his election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] In December 1778, Henry sent an urgent appeal to Congress for naval aid in protecting Chesapeake Bay.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] None was forthcoming, and on May 8, 1779, in the final days of Henry's governorship, British ships under Sir George Collier entered the bay, landed troops, and took Portsmouth and Suffolk, destroying valuable supplies.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p01] The British departed on May 24, and Henry, limited to three consecutive terms in office by the 1776 constitution, left office soon after, succeeded by Jefferson, and with his family returned to Leatherwood.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] At Leatherwood, Henry devoted himself to local affairs in the thinly-populated county and was given seats on the county court (the local governing body), as prominent landowners were, and on the parish vestry.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He refused to be elected a delegate to Congress, stating that his personal business and past illness made that impossible.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] When Governor Jefferson sent a note to him in early 1780, Henry replied with gratitude, complaining of his isolation, and wrote of his many concerns about the state of affairs as the war continued.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The freeholders of Henry County soon thereafter sent its eponym to the House of Delegates.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] But within weeks, health problems recurred, causing his return to Leatherwood.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] While in Richmond (where the capital had been moved) Henry opposed a congressional plan to revalue Continental currency and impose certain taxes, feeling it would mostly benefit the North.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He was successful in defeating it, but after he left Richmond, supporters persuaded the legislature to pass it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Once he returned home, he was heavily involved in efforts to recruit local volunteers to suppress bands of Loyalists who were conducting raids in the frontier area.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry rode with the troops, though he did not lead them, and they were generally successful in suppressing the resistance.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The volunteers were disbanded in September 1780.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In January 1781, British forces under the renegade former American general Benedict Arnold sailed up the James River and captured Richmond with little opposition as Henry joined the other legislators and Governor Jefferson in fleeing to Charlottesville.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Although Arnold soon withdrew to Portsmouth, in February, troops under Lord Cornwallis entered the state from North Carolina; the war, which had for the most part been fought out of state, would have many of its final moves played in Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] With Washington's army near New York, Henry sought to recruit soldiers to defend the state and in March helped draft an angry remonstrance from the House of Delegates to Congress, demanding help.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Nevertheless, in May, British forces under Colonel Banastre Tarleton raided Charlottesville, nearly capturing the Virginia government, which fled to Staunton.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] There is a story that Henry fled with other prominent leaders and sought refuge at the home of a woman who initially spurned them as cowards for fleeing Charlottesville.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] But on learning Henry was with the group, she decided it must be all right, and offered them the best she had.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Jefferson did not go to Staunton: his term as governor had just expired, but the legislature had not met to hold an election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] After the raid, he took refuge at his farm in Bedford County, and Virginia had no governor for ten days.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Several legislators complained of Jefferson's actions and called for an inquiry into the conduct of the executive (Jefferson and his council), and Henry was among those who took the lead.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The resolution passed, but the inquiry was set for the next session, and the legislature thought better of it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Jefferson was angered at Henry's actions and held a grudge that did not abate until well after Henry's death in 1799.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] With the war effectively ended by the American victory at the siege of Yorktown, Henry served as delegate from his county through 1784, when he was elected again as governor.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Peace brought many adjustments, and Henry sponsored legislation to reform Virginia's currency and to adjust payments from contracts still outstanding from before periods of high inflation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Jefferson and others wanted to reopen contracts that had been already settled but in depreciated currency; Henry thought that unjust, and because of his influence in the General Assembly, his version prevailed.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This had international implications, as some of the creditors were British, who sought payment in hard money rather than the depreciated currency that had been paid into escrow.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] At the May 1783 House of Delegates session, Henry successfully sponsored a resolution to repeal the trade embargo against Britain.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] That passed despite opposition from Speaker John Tyler Sr.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry also introduced legislation to permit Loyalists to return to Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] There was considerable opposition to that, and the measure was held over until later in the year, by which time public sentiment had been gauged through meetings in each county.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry spoke in the debate, asking "shall we, who have laid the proud British lion at our feet, be frightened of its whelps?" Once it was amended (though in what way is not clear), the bill passed in November 1783.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry worked together with James Madison, a delegate after three years in Congress, on a number of issues.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] They differed, though, on state support for Virginia's Protestant churches.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was not alone in this belief; both Washington and Lee supported such plans.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Madison believed that Henry took the position for family reasons—his wife and children were likely quite happy to be in Richmond rather than in remote Henry County—but the cost was Henry's bill as Madison got it postponed to the following year and eventually defeated.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Instead, Madison got Jefferson's Statute for Religious Freedom through the legislature.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This law requiring a separation of church and state passed the General Assembly in 1786.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry's second time as governor was for two years, as the legislature re-elected him in 1785.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] It was, generally, more placid than his first.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] During this time, Henry and his family lived at "Salisbury", in Chesterfield County, about 13 miles (21 km) from Richmond in open country that he rented, though he had an official residence close to the Virginia Capitol, which was then under construction.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The General Assembly had passed legislation for new arms for the militia, and Henry worked with Lafayette to have them sent from France.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Each county's militia was under firm local control, a state of affairs that had resulted in problems during the war as local militia refused orders from Henry and other governors when asked to serve out of state or conscript recruits into the Continental Army.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In 1784, seeking to bring the militias under central control, the General Assembly passed an act terminating all militia officer commissions and allowing Henry, with the consent of the Governor's Council, to appoint replacements.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The Virginia Constitution required that there be a recommendation from the county court.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Instead of asking the county court, Henry solicited recommendations from prominent citizens in each county whom he or his council members knew.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The result was near revolt in the counties, as citizens protested the act as unconstitutional, and counties refused to obey.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The law went widely unenforced, and in October 1785, Henry requested the legislators to repeal it; they complied the following year.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Residents of western North Carolina, what is today the state of Tennessee, sought to separate and become the State of Franklin.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] A former delegate, Arthur Campbell, wanted to join Virginia's adjacent Washington County as part of the scheme in 1785.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry had Campbell removed as a militia officer and from his other county offices, as well as ousting Campbell's supporters, replacing them with residents of known loyalty.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry also sought to advance Virginia's development, both as governor and through his personal investments.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He backed schemes to open navigation on the upper Potomac and James rivers, envisioning canals to connect them to the Ohio River Valley.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He also supported a scheme to develop a canal across the Great Dismal Swamp, believing that with it, the trade of eastern North Carolina would flow through Norfolk.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He owned land along the proposed route and sought to interest General Washington in the scheme but was not successful.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Despite Henry's support for internal improvements, he failed to notify Virginia's representatives of their appointment to meet with Maryland over navigation on the Potomac, and only two, including George Mason, attended what became known as the Mount Vernon Conference in 1785.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Randolph, unable to attend because of lack of timely notification, hinted that the reason for Henry's neglect was not forgetfulness but a growing hostility towards things federal.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In 1786, Henry was more assiduous in notifying delegates to the Annapolis Conference called with the support of Madison, who was appointed a delegate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry stepped down at the end of his fifth term, stating he needed to devote time to his family and earn money to support it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Disinclined to return to distant Leatherwood after his time as governor ended in November 1786, Henry hoped to purchase land in Hanover County but bought property in Prince Edward County instead.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Hampden-Sydney College, which he had helped found in 1775, is located in that county, and Henry enrolled his sons there.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The local freeholders elected Henry to the House of Delegates in early 1787, and he served there until the end of 1790.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Governor Randolph offered to make Henry a delegate to the Constitutional Convention, scheduled to meet in Philadelphia later that year to consider changes to the Articles of Confederation, the document that had governed the loose union among the states since 1777.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry refused the appointment, alleging it would be difficult financially.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry's record of urging unity made him a potential supporter of a closer bond between the states, and as late as the end of 1786, Madison hoped for Henry as an ally in the fight.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Several factors had eroded Henry's trust in the Northern states, including what he deemed Congress's failure to send adequate troops to protect Virginia settlers in the Ohio River Valley.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was outraged by the Jay–Gardoqui Treaty, which would have ceded exclusive navigation on the Mississippi River to Spain for 25 years.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This was in exchange for commercial concessions that would benefit New England, where there was a growing separatist movement.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Northern votes were sufficient to relax John Jay's negotiating instructions, which had originally forbidden restricting American navigation on the Mississippi, to allow him to reach a deal; Southern votes were sufficient to block the treaty's ratification.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] These events caused Henry and some other Virginia leaders to feel betrayed and to have little trust in the good faith of the North.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] When the Philadelphia convention adjourned in September 1787, its president, Washington, returned home and immediately sent a copy of the new Constitution to Henry, recommending he support it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was in Richmond for the autumn legislative session as delegate for Prince Edward County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] While thanking Washington for presiding in Philadelphia and for sending the document, he said of it, "I have to lament that I cannot bring my Mind to accord with the proposed Constitution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The Concern I feel on this account is really greater than I am able to express." He hinted, though, that he was still open to changing his mind.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This allowed Henry to remain noncommittal as opponents of the Constitution, such as Mason and Edmund Randolph (both delegates at Philadelphia) published their opinions, and to refine his views.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In the initial Virginia battle over the Constitution, the call for a convention to decide whether the state should ratify it, Henry and Mason were among those who supported allowing the convention to ratify it, conditional on amendments being made.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The matter was compromised with language allowing the convention's members full rein in deciding what to do, and it was set for June 1788, with elections in March; both those who supported it and those who did not felt time would be to their advantage.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry opposed the Constitution because of its grant of a strong executive, the president; he had not fought to free Virginia from King George to surrender such powers to what might prove a despot.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry accordingly deemed the Constitution a backwards step and a betrayal of those who had died in the Revolutionary cause.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] At the Virginia Ratifying Convention, which began on June 2, 1788, according to Kidd, Henry's "personality blazed in all its power and glory." Henry suggested that the framers of the Constitution had no right to begin it "We the People" and ignore the powers of the states.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He suggested that the document put too much power in the hands of too few.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Madison, the lead supporter of the Constitution, was inhibited in replying to Henry's criticisms, since he was ill through most of the convention.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry likely realized he was fighting a losing battle as sentiment in the convention moved towards ratification, but he continued to speak at length, and his speeches fill nearly one-quarter of the pages of the Richmond convention's debates.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Governor Randolph, who had become a supporter of ratification, suggested that if the convention allowed Henry to continue arguing, it would last six months rather than six weeks.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] After the convention voted on June 25 to ratify the Constitution, Henry was somewhat mollified by the fact that the convention had proposed about 40 amendments; some of them were later incorporated in the Bill of Rights.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Mason, Henry's ally in opposing ratification, intended a fiery diatribe on the faults of the new plan of government; he was talked out of it.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] By one account, Henry told other opponents that he had done his duty in opposing ratification, and as republicans, with the issues settled in a democratic way, they had best all go home.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Madison wrote to Washington that Henry still hoped for amendments to weaken the power of the federal government, possibly to be proposed by a second national convention.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry returned to the House of Delegates where he successfully defeated Madison's effort to become federal senator from Virginia, for under the original Constitution senators were elected by legislators, not the people.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Although Henry made it clear he would not serve in office outside Virginia, he received a number of votes in the election.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Madison gained election to the House of Representatives in a district where he was opposed by James Monroe, though Madison's supporters complained that Henry's supporters in the legislature had unfairly placed Orange County, Madison's home county, in a district leaning anti-Federalist.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry also saw to it that the requested amendments were incorporated in petitions from the legislature to the federal Congress.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Despite his qualms, Henry served as one of Virginia's presidential electors, voting for Washington (elected President) and John Adams (elected Vice President).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was disappointed when the First Congress passed only amendments dealing with personal liberties, not those designed to weaken the government.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] A final cause Henry engaged in before leaving the House of Delegates at the end of 1790 was over the Funding Act of 1790, by which the federal government took over the debts of the states, much of which dated from the Revolutionary War.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] On November 3, 1790, Henry introduced a resolution which was passed by the House of Delegates and by the state Senate, declaring the act "repugnant to the constitution of the United States, as it goes to the exercise of a power not granted to the general [federal] government".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This would prove the first of many resolutions passed by Southern state legislatures in the decades to come, defending states' rights and strict interpretation of the Constitution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Leaving the House of Delegates after 1790, Henry found himself in debt, owing in part to expenses while governor, and sought to secure his family's fortune through land speculation and a return to the practice of law.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Not fully reconciled to the federal government, Henry contemplated a new republic in the sparsely settled frontier lands, but his plans came to nothing.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He did not travel as widely for cases as he had in the 1760s, confining his practice mostly to Prince Edward and Bedford counties, though in a compelling case, or for a large enough fee, he would travel to Richmond or over the mountains to Greenbrier County (today in West Virginia).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] When the new federal court opened in Virginia in 1790, British creditors promptly filed over a hundred cases seeking to enforce claims from the Revolutionary War.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was part of the defense team in *Jones v.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Walker* before the federal court in 1791; his co-counsel included John Marshall, who prepared the written pleadings while Henry did much of the courtroom advocacy.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry argued the case for three days; Marshall, looking back, called him "a great orator ... and much more, a learned lawyer, a most accurate thinker, and a profound reasoner".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The case ended inconclusively after one of the judges died, but the legal teams reassembled for the case of *Ware v.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Argued before another three-judge panel that included Chief Justice of the United States John Jay and Associate Justice James Iredell, Henry's argument provoked Justice Iredell to exclaim, "Gracious God!
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He is an orator indeed." Henry and Marshall were initially successful, but the plaintiffs appealed, and after Marshall argued his only case before the Supreme Court, that court in 1796 ruled for the British creditors.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry's friendship with Washington had cooled somewhat amid the ratification debates, but by 1794, both men were looking to reconcile.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry found himself more aligned with Washington than with Jefferson and Madison, and Washington still considered himself indebted to Henry for notifying him about the Conway Cabal.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Washington offered Henry a seat on the Supreme Court in 1794, but he refused, feeling his family needed him.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Washington also tried to get Henry to accept positions as Secretary of State and as minister to Spain, and Virginia Governor "Light-Horse" Harry Lee wanted to appoint him to the Senate.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry's continuing popularity in Virginia made him an attractive ally, and even Jefferson tried to recruit him, sending word though a mutual friend that he bore no grudge.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] After Washington made it clear he would not seek a third term in 1796, Marshall and Lee discussed a possible Henry run for president with him, but Henry was unwilling.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The General Assembly elected him as governor again that year, but he declined, citing age and health.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry's refusal to accept these offices increased his popularity as he was, like Washington, seen as a Cincinnatus, giving up power to return to his farm and his plow.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry sold his property in Prince Edward County in 1792, moving with his family to Long Island, a plantation in Campbell County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In 1794, Henry purchased Red Hill near Brookneal, Virginia in Charlotte County, where he and his family lived much of the year, though they moved to Long Island in the "sickly season".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was gratified at the election of his old friend John Adams as president in 1796 over his foe Jefferson, but Henry's commitment to the Federalist Party was tested by the repressive Alien and Sedition Acts of 1798.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He chose to say nothing but supported the campaign of Marshall, a moderate Federalist, for the House of Representatives; Marshall won narrowly.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was under considerable pressure from Virginia Federalists to return to politics, but it was not until former president Washington urged him to run for the legislature in early 1799 that Henry gave in.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Turning down an offer from President Adams to make him an envoy to France, Henry was elected as delegate from Charlotte County on March 4, 1799.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The legislature had no immediate session scheduled, so he returned to Red Hill and never left again, dying there of intussusception at his home on June 6, 1799.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In Henry's will, he left his estates and his 67 slaves to be divided between his wife and his six sons.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He did not free any slaves, despite his speeches against enslavement by tyrants and despite his various comments opposing the institution of slavery itself.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The tributes to Henry upon his death were many.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The *Virginia Gazette* printed a death notice bordered in black, "As long as our rivers flow, or mountains stand, Virginia ... will say to rising generations, imitate my H E N R Y".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The *Petersburg Intelligencer* regretted the death of a man who might have been able "to conciliate all parties and produce that harmony and accord" needed at a time of national controversy.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The *Argus*, a paper which supported Jefferson's faction, noted that Henry "pointed out those evils in our Constitution ... against which we now complain ...
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Several of Henry's homes are recognized for their association with him.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Scotchtown Plantation is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The Red Hill Patrick Henry National Memorial preserves Henry's final home, gravesite, and law office.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The site of his birthplace, which burned in 1807 and is now reduced to archaeological remains, is also preserved; it is listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] A plaque placed by the Daughters of the American Revolution marks the site of Leatherwood in Henry County.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry helped found Hampden-Sydney College, believing that "every free state" should promote "useful knowledge amongst its citizens".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He was an original trustee and sent seven of his sons there.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry was instrumental in getting its charter passed by the General Assembly in 1783.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Emory and Henry University in Emory, Virginia was named for him and John Emory, an early bishop in Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Fort Henry stood in what is now Wheeling, West Virginia, but was at the time part of Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] It was built in 1774 and named Fort Fincastle after one of Lord Dunmore's titles but was renamed for Henry, then governor, after independence.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Fort Patrick Henry was built during the American Revolutionary War along the South Fork Holston River at the present-day site of Kingsport, Tennessee.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This fort serves as the namesake of Fort Patrick Henry Dam and its reservoir on the river.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] At least four ships have been named in Henry's honor: the passenger and freight packet ship *Patrick Henry*, the Civil War Confederate Navy steamboat CSS *Patrick Henry*, the World War II Liberty ship SS *Patrick Henry* and the ballistic missile submarine USS *Patrick Henry* (SSBN-599).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Camp Patrick Henry was a World War II-era military camp near Newport News, Virginia.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Decommissioned in 1946, it became the site of the Newport News/Williamsburg International Airport on 925 acres (3.74 km2).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] When opened in 1949, the airport was called Patrick Henry Field and was later renamed Patrick Henry International Airport, a name it retained until 1990.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Patrick Henry has been honored twice on U.S. postage stamps.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] On October 7, 1955, the United States Post Office Department issued a $1 definitive stamp honoring Henry, one of the high values in the Liberty issue.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] A painting of Henry by American artist Alonzo Chappel was used as the inspiration and as the model by the engraver for this issue.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Post Office issued the American Credo series, six stamps with well-known patriotic quotations.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Patrick Henry's most famous words are inscribed on the final issue in the series, a 4-cent stamp first released in Richmond on January 11, 1961.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] As historian Richard Beeman put it, Henry was a man who "did not bother to write much of anything down", a handicap when being evaluated by history.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] The lack of primary source materials regarding Henry—only a handful of papers and a few of his speeches survive—has frustrated Henry's biographers from Wirt (1817) to Beeman (1974).
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Two years before publishing his book, Wirt commented: "It is all speaking, speaking, speaking.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] 'Tis true he could talk—Gods! how he *could* talk! but ... to make the matter worse, from 1763 to 1789 ... not one of his speeches lives in print, writing or memory".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Beeman, for his part, concludes, "the Revolutionary firebrand, whatever his achievements, possessed a miserable sense of history".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] This was a deficiency not possessed by Jefferson, who not only survived Henry by a quarter century, but who got to fill the vacuum of information about Henry with his own recollections and opinions.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Wirt did not print many of Jefferson's criticisms of Henry, who had irritated Jefferson to such an extent he was still criticizing Henry to guests at Monticello in 1824.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Jefferson's negative assessments of Henry, whether justified or not, have adversely affected Henry's historical reputation.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry has always been acclaimed by Americans for the brilliance of his political oratory.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] His career pointed the transition from the political squirearchy of the eighteenth century to the mass politics of Andrew Jackson's day".
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In his study of Henry's oratory, David A.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] McCants suggests that Henry's position as great American orator of his day was not so much because of his "heroism and eloquence" but for adapting the clashing philosophies, religious and political, that met in Henry's Virginia, to create a new style of oratory that appealed to the masses.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Kidd argues that the historical focus on the quality of Henry's oratory may result from a discomfort with the content of his speeches, especially his opposition to the Constitution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] During the Civil War era, both sides claimed Henry as a partisan, abolitionists citing his writings against slavery, and those sympathetic to the Southern cause pointing to his hostility to the Constitution.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] That opposition by Henry came to be seen by many writers, even those friendly to Henry, as a blot on an otherwise admirable career.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Henry has been cited as a hero to both Left and Right but has become a particular favorite of the latter.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] He is especially attractive to Christian conservatives, who cite his deep religious beliefs as well as his writings and speeches in favor of Christian virtue and in defense of religious liberty.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] Because Henry was educated at home by his father, he has become a symbol of the homeschooling movement.
[src:1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election/patrick-henry-p02] In 2000, Patrick Henry College was founded in Purcellville, Virginia, in large part for those who had been homeschooled.
